This paper is about neural machine translation (NMT), which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP) and falls under the computer science category of "Computation and Language" (cs.CL). The paper discusses the use of character-level input for NMT, which involves processing individual characters rather than words or word fragments. This topic is closely related to deep learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI), as it involves training neural networks to perform language translation tasks. Additionally, the paper discusses techniques for reducing computation time, which is a common concern in neural network research and falls under the category of "Neural and Evolutionary Computing" (cs.NE). Finally, the paper evaluates the performance of these techniques using various metrics, which is a common practice in computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning research.
